title: Sets satisfying the Generalized Continuum Hypothesis

blocks.name: cgch
blocks.content: Extend class notation to include the collection of sets that satisfy the GCH.
blocks.origin: const class cgch { GCH }

diff.cgch.c
diff.cgch.w
df-gch
blocks.content: Define the collection of "GCH-sets", or sets for which the generalized continuum hypothesis holds. In this language the generalized continuum hypothesis can be expressed as ` GCH = _V ` . A set ` x ` satisfies the generalized continuum hypothesis if it is finite or there is no set ` y ` strictly between ` x ` and its powerset in cardinality. The continuum hypothesis is equivalent to ` _om e. GCH ` . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 15-May-2015.)

blocks.name: elgch
blocks.content: Elementhood in the collection of GCH-sets. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 15-May-2015.)
blocks.origin:

  -| diffsc(s0, c0)
} = {
  syl5bb(wcel(c0, c1), wcel(c0, cgch), wo(wcel(c0, cfn), wal(s0, wn(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(c0)))))), wo(wcel(c0, cfn), wcel(c0, cab(hs0, wal(s0, wn(wa(wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(cv(hs0))))))))))
  bitri(wcel(c0, cgch), wo(wcel(c0, cfn), wcel(c0, cab(hs0, wal(s0, wn(wa(wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(cv(hs0))))))))), wcel(c0, cun(cfn, cab(hs0, wal(s0, wn(wa(wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(cv(hs0))))))))))
  eleq2i(c0, cgch, cun(cfn, cab(hs0, wal(s0, wn(wa(wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(cv(hs0)))))))))
  df-gch(hs0, s0)
  elun(c0, cfn, cab(hs0, wal(s0, wn(wa(wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(cv(hs0))))))))
  orbi2d(wcel(c0, c1), wcel(c0, cfn), wcel(c0, cab(hs0, wal(s0, wn(wa(wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(cv(hs0)))))))), wal(s0, wn(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(c0))))))
  elabg(hs0, c0, c1, wal(s0, wn(wa(wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(cv(hs0)))))), wal(s0, wn(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(c0))))))
  albidv(s0, wceq(cv(hs0), c0), wn(wa(wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(cv(hs0))))), wn(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(c0)))))
  notbid(wceq(cv(hs0), c0), wa(wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(cv(hs0)))), wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(c0))))
  anbi12d(wceq(cv(hs0), c0), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(cv(hs0))), wbr(c0, csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(c0)))
  breq1(cv(hs0), c0, csdm, cv(s0))
  breq2d(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(cv(hs0)), cpw(c0), wceq(cv(hs0), c0))
  pweq(cv(hs0), c0)
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
  diff.hs0.w(wal(s0, wn(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(s0)), wbr(cv(s0), csdm, cpw(c0))))))
  diff.wceq.s(s0, cv(hs0), c0)
  diff.cv.s(s0, hs0)
  diffss.ex(s0, hs0)
  diff.hs0.s(s0)
}

blocks.name: fingch
blocks.content: A finite set is a GCH-set. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 15-May-2015.)

blocks.name: gchi
blocks.content: The only GCH-sets which have other sets between it and its power set are finite sets. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 15-May-2015.)
blocks.origin:
thm gchi(class c0, class c1) {
  |- wi(w3a(wcel(c0, cgch), wbr(c0, csdm, c1), wbr(c1, csdm, cpw(c0))), wcel(c0, cfn))
} = {
  3impib(wcel(c0, cgch), wbr(c0, csdm, c1), wbr(c1, csdm, cpw(c0)), wcel(c0, cfn))
  syl5(wcel(c0, cgch), wa(wbr(c0, csdm, c1), wbr(c1, csdm, cpw(c0))), wcel(c0, cfn), wn(wal(hs0, wn(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0)))))))
  sylib(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, c1), wbr(c1, csdm, cpw(c0))), wn(wal(hs0, wn(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0)))))), wex(hs0, wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0)))))
  mpcom(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, c1), wbr(c1, csdm, cpw(c0))), wex(hs0, wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0)))), wcel(c1, universe))
  adantl(wbr(c0, csdm, c1), wbr(c1, csdm, cpw(c0)), wcel(c1, universe))
  brrelex1i(c1, csdm, cpw(c0))
  relsdom()
  spcegv(hs0, c1, universe, wa(wbr(c0, csdm, c1), wbr(c1, csdm, cpw(c0))), wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0))))
  anbi12d(wceq(cv(hs0), c1), wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0)), wbr(c0, csdm, c1), wbr(c1, csdm, cpw(c0)))
  breq2(cv(hs0), c1, c0, csdm)
  breq1(cv(hs0), c1, csdm, cpw(c0))
  df-ex(hs0, wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0))))
  ord(wcel(c0, cgch), wal(hs0, wn(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0))))), wcel(c0, cfn))
  orcomd(wcel(c0, cgch), wal(hs0, wn(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0))))), wcel(c0, cfn))
  ibi(wcel(c0, cgch), wo(wcel(c0, cfn), wal(hs0, wn(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0)))))))
  elgch(hs0, c0, cgch)
  diff.hs0.c(c1)
  diff.hs0.w(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, c1), wbr(c1, csdm, cpw(c0))))
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
}

  mpcom((c0[‚â∫]c1 ‚àß c1[‚â∫]P(c0)), ‚àÉ(hs0,(c0[‚â∫]hs0 ‚àß hs0[‚â∫]P(c0))), c1 ‚àà ùïå)

  anbi12d(hs0 = c1, c0[‚â∫]hs0, hs0[‚â∫]P(c0), c0[‚â∫]c1, c1[‚â∫]P(c0))

  orcomd(c0 ‚àà GCH, ‚àÄ(hs0, ¬¨(c0[‚â∫]hs0 ‚àß hs0[‚â∫]P(c0))), c0 ‚àà Fin)
  ibi(c0 ‚àà GCH, (c0 ‚àà Fin ‚à® ‚àÄ(hs0, ¬¨(c0[‚â∫]hs0 ‚àß hs0[‚â∫]P(c0)))))
  elgch(hs0, c0, cgch)
  diff.hs0.c(c1)
  diff.hs0.w((c0[‚â∫]c1 ‚àß c1[‚â∫]P(c0)))
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
}

blocks.name: gchen1
blocks.content: If ` A <_ B < ~P A ` , and ` A ` is an infinite GCH-set, then ` A = B ` in cardinality. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 15-May-2015.)

blocks.name: gchen2
blocks.content: If ` A < B <_ ~P A ` , and ` A ` is an infinite GCH-set, then ` B = ~P A ` in cardinality. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 15-May-2015.)

blocks.name: gchor
blocks.content: If ` A <_ B <_ ~P A ` , and ` A ` is an infinite GCH-set, then either ` A = B ` or ` B = ~P A ` in cardinality. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 15-May-2015.)

blocks.name: engch
blocks.content: The property of being a GCH-set is a cardinal invariant. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 15-May-2015.)
blocks.origin:
thm engch(class c0, class c1) {
  |- wi(wbr(c0, cen, c1), wb(wcel(c0, cgch), wcel(c1, cgch)))
} = {
  3bitr4d(wbr(c0, cen, c1), wcel(c0, cgch), wcel(c1, cgch), wo(wcel(c0, cfn), wal(hs0, wn(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0)))))), wo(wcel(c1, cfn), wal(hs0, wn(wa(wbr(c1, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c1)))))))
  orbi12d(wbr(c0, cen, c1), wcel(c0, cfn), wal(hs0, wn(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0))))), wcel(c1, cfn), wal(hs0, wn(wa(wbr(c1, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c1))))))
  enfi(c0, c1)
  albidv(hs0, wbr(c0, cen, c1), wn(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0)))), wn(wa(wbr(c1, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c1)))))
  notbid(wbr(c0, cen, c1), wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0))), wa(wbr(c1, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c1))))
  anbi12d(wbr(c0, cen, c1), wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0)), wbr(c1, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c1)))
  sdomen1(c0, c1, cv(hs0))
  syl(wbr(c0, cen, c1), wb(wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c1))), wbr(cpw(c0), cen, cpw(c1)))
  pwen(c0, c1)
  sdomen2(cpw(c0), cpw(c1), cv(hs0))
  syl(wbr(c0, cen, c1), wb(wcel(c0, cgch), wo(wcel(c0, cfn), wal(hs0, wn(wa(wbr(c0, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c0))))))), wcel(c0, universe))
  brrelex1i(c0, cen, c1)
  elgch(hs0, c0, universe)
  syl(wbr(c0, cen, c1), wb(wcel(c1, cgch), wo(wcel(c1, cfn), wal(hs0, wn(wa(wbr(c1, csdm, cv(hs0)), wbr(cv(hs0), csdm, cpw(c1))))))), wcel(c1, universe))
  brrelex2i(c0, cen, c1)
  relen()
  elgch(hs0, c1, universe)
  diff.hs0.w(wbr(c0, cen, c1))
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
  diff.hs0.c(c1)
}

blocks.name: gchdomtri
blocks.content: Under certain conditions, a GCH-set can demonstrate trichotomy of dominance. Lemma for ~ gchac . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 15-May-2015.)
blocks.origin:
thm gchdomtri(class c0, class c1) {
  |- wi(w3a(wcel(c0, cgch), wbr(co(c0, ccda, c0), cen, c0), wbr(c1, cdom, cpw(c0))), wo(wbr(c0, cdom, c1), wbr(c1, cdom, c0)))
} = {
  pm2.61dan(w3a(wcel(c0, cgch), wbr(co(c0, ccda, c0), cen, c0), wbr(c1, cdom, cpw(c0))), wo(wbr(c0, cdom, c1), wbr(c1, cdom, c0)), wcel(c0, cfn))
  orrd(wa(w3a(wcel(c0, cgch), wbr(co(c0, ccda, c0), cen, c0), wbr(c1, cdom, cpw(c0))), wcel(c0, cfn)), wbr(c0, cdom, c1), wbr(c1, cdom, c0))
  syl5ibr(wa(w3a(wcel(c0, cgch), wbr(co(c0, ccda, c0), cen, c0), wbr(c1, cdom, cpw(c0))), wcel(c0, cfn)), wn(wbr(c0, cdom, c1)), wbr(c1, cdom, c0), wn(wbr(c0, csdm, c1)))
  con3i(wbr(c0, cdom, c1), wbr(c0, csdm, c1))
  sdomdom(c0, c1)
  sylan(w3a(wcel(c0, cgch), wbr(co(c0, ccda, c0), cen, c0), wbr(c1, cdom, cpw(c0))), wcel(c0, cfn), wb(wbr(c1, cdom, c0), wn(wbr(c0, csdm, c1))), wcel(c1, universe))

blocks.content: Lemma for ~ fpwwe2 . Given two well-orders ` <. X , R >. ` and ` <. Y , S >. ` of parts of ` A ` , one is an initial segment of the other. (The ` O C_ P ` hypothesis is in order to break the symmetry of ` X ` and ` Y ` .) (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 15-May-2015.) (Proof shortened by Peter Mazsa, 23-Sep-2022.)

blocks.content: Lemma for ~ fpwwe2 . Given two well-orders ` <. X , R >. ` and ` <. Y , S >. ` of parts of ` A ` , one is an initial segment of the other. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 15-May-2015.)

thm fpwwe2lem10(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, setvar s3, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4, class c5, class c6, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, wo(wa(wss(c0, c1), wceq(c2, cin(c3, cxp(c1, c0)))), wa(wss(c1, c0), wceq(c3, cin(c2, cxp(c0, c1))))))
  -| wceq(c4, copab(s0, s1, wa(wa(wss(cv(s0), c5), wss(cv(s1), cxp(cv(s0), cv(s0)))), wa(wwe(cv(s1), cv(s0)), wral(s2, cv(s0), wsbc(s3, cima(ccnv(cv(s1)), csn(cv(s2))), wceq(co(cv(s3), c6, cin(cv(s1), cxp(cv(s3), cv(s3)))), cv(s2))))))))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c5, universe))
  -| wi(wa(w0, w3a(wss(cv(s0), c5), wss(cv(s1), cxp(cv(s0), cv(s0))), wwe(cv(s1), cv(s0)))), wcel(co(cv(s0), c6, cv(s1)), c5))
  -| wi(w0, wbr(c0, c4, c2))

  -| diffss(s0, s1)

  mpi(w0, wo(wa(wss(c0, c1), wceq(c2, cin(c3, cxp(c1, c0)))), wa(wss(c1, c0), wceq(c3, cin(c2, cxp(c0, c1))))), wo(wss(cdm(coi(c2, c0)), cdm(coi(c3, c1))), wss(cdm(coi(c3, c1)), cdm(coi(c2, c0)))))

blocks.name: fpwwe2
blocks.content: Given any function ` F ` from well-orderings of subsets of ` A ` to ` A ` , there is a unique well-ordered subset ` <. X , ( W `` X ) >. ` which "agrees" with ` F ` in the sense that each initial segment maps to its upper bound, and such that the entire set maps to an element of the set (so that it cannot be extended without losing the well-ordering). This theorem can be used to prove ~ dfac8a . Theorem 1.1 of [KanamoriPincus] p. 415. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 18-May-2015.)
blocks.origin:

blocks.name: fpwwe
blocks.content: Given any function ` F ` from the powerset of ` A ` to ` A ` , ~ canth2 gives that the function is not injective, but we can say rather more than that. There is a unique well-ordered subset ` <. X , ( W `` X ) >. ` which "agrees" with ` F ` in the sense that each initial segment maps to its upper bound, and such that the entire set maps to an element of the set (so that it cannot be extended without losing the well-ordering). This theorem can be used to prove ~ dfac8a . Theorem 1.1 of [KanamoriPincus] p. 415. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 18-May-2015.)

blocks.name: canth4
blocks.content: An "effective" form of Cantor's theorem ~ canth . For any function ` F ` from the powerset of ` A ` to ` A ` , there are two definable sets ` B ` and ` C ` which witness non-injectivity of ` F ` . Corollary 1.3 of [KanamoriPincus] p. 416. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 18-May-2015.)

blocks.content: A slightly stronger form of Cantor's theorem: For ` 1 < n ` , ` n + 1 < 2 ^ n ` . Corollary 1.6 of [KanamoriPincus] p. 417. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 18-May-2015.)

blocks.name: finngch
blocks.content: The exclusion of finite sets from consideration in ~ df-gch is necessary, because otherwise finite sets larger than a singleton would violate the GCH property. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 10-Jun-2015.)

blocks.name: gchcda1
blocks.content: An infinite GCH-set is idempotent under cardinal successor. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 18-May-2015.)

} = {

  mpdan(wa(wcel(c0, cgch), wn(wcel(c0, cfn))), wbr(c0, cen, co(c0, ccda, c1o)), wa(wbr(c0, cdom, co(c0, ccda, c1o)), wbr(co(c0, ccda, c1o), csdm, cpw(c0))))
  jca(wa(wcel(c0, cgch), wn(wcel(c0, cfn))), wbr(c0, cdom, co(c0, ccda, c1o)), wbr(co(c0, ccda, c1o), csdm, cpw(c0)))
  sylan2(wcel(c0, cgch), wn(wcel(c0, cfn)), wbr(c0, cdom, co(c0, ccda, c1o)), wcel(c1o, com))
  a1i(wn(wcel(c0, cfn)), wcel(c1o, com))

  mt3d(wa(wcel(c0, cgch), wn(wcel(c0, cfn))), wbr(c1o, csdm, c0), wcel(c0, cfn))
  simpr(wcel(c0, cgch), wn(wcel(c0, cfn)))
  sylbird(wa(wcel(c0, cgch), wn(wcel(c0, cfn))), wn(wbr(c1o, csdm, c0)), wcel(c0, cfn), wbr(c0, cdom, c1o))
  sylan2(wcel(c0, cgch), wn(wcel(c0, cfn)), wb(wbr(c0, cdom, c1o), wn(wbr(c1o, csdm, c0))), wcel(c1o, cfn))

blocks.name: gchinf
blocks.content: An infinite GCH-set is Dedekind-infinite. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 31-May-2015.)

blocks.name: pwfseqlem4
blocks.content: Lemma for ~ pwfseq . Derive a final contradiction from the function ` F ` in ~ pwfseqlem3 . Applying ~ fpwwe2 to it, we get a certain maximal well-ordered subset ` Z ` , but the defining property ` ( Z F ( W `` Z ) ) e. Z ` contradicts our assumption on ` F ` , so we are reduced to the case of ` Z ` finite. This too is a contradiction, though, because ` Z ` and its preimage under ` ( W `` Z ) ` are distinct sets of the same cardinality and in a subset relation, which is impossible for finite sets. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 31-May-2015.)

blocks.name: pwfseqlem5
blocks.content: Lemma for ~ pwfseq . Although in some ways ~ pwfseqlem4 is the "main" part of the proof, one last aspect which makes up a remark in the original text is by far the hardest part to formalize. The main proof relies on the existence of an injection ` K ` from the set of finite sequences on an infinite set ` x ` to ` x ` . Now this alone would not be difficult to prove; this is mostly the claim of ~ fseqen . However, what is needed for the proof is a _canonical_ injection on these sets, so we have to start from scratch pulling together explicit bijections from the lemmas. If one attempts such a program, it will mostly go through, but there is one key step which is inherently nonconstructive, namely the proof of ~ infxpen . The resolution is not obvious, but it turns out that reversing an infinite ordinal's Cantor normal form absorbs all the non-leading terms ( ~ cnfcom3c ), which can be used to construct a pairing function explicitly using properties of the ordinal exponential ( ~ infxpenc ). (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 31-May-2015.)

blocks.name: pwfseq
blocks.content: The powerset of a Dedekind-infinite set does not inject into the set of finite sequences. The proof is due to Halbeisen and Shelah. Proposition 1.7 of [KanamoriPincus] p. 418. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 31-May-2015.)

blocks.name: pwxpndom2
blocks.content: The powerset of a Dedekind-infinite set does not inject into its Cartesian product with itself. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 31-May-2015.) (Proof shortened by AV, 18-Jul-2022.)
blocks.origin:
thm pwxpndom2(class c0) {
  |- wi(wbr(com, cdom, c0), wn(wbr(cpw(c0), cdom, co(c0, ccda, cxp(c0, c0)))))
} = {

blocks.name: gch-kn
blocks.content: The equivalence of two versions of the Generalized Continuum Hypothesis. The right-hand side is the standard version in the literature. The left-hand side is a version devised by Kannan Nambiar, which he calls the Axiom of Combinatorial Sets. For the notation and motivation behind this axiom, see his paper, "Derivation of Continuum Hypothesis from Axiom of Combinatorial Sets", available at ~ http://www.e-atheneum.net/science/derivation_ch.pdf . The equivalence of the two sides provides a negative answer to Open Problem 2 in ~ http://www.e-atheneum.net/science/open_problem_print.pdf . The key idea in the proof below is to equate both sides of ~ alephexp2 to the successor aleph using ~ enen2 . (Contributed by NM, 1-Oct-2004.)
